\pard\widctlpar\b\fs32 2.Variables\b0\fs22\par
\b\fs28 2.a\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\f0\fs22 2.a.1 What are Variables?\par
\cf1\b0 Variables come from mathematics.They are abstract concepts in a programming language to store the results of computations.They are commonly accessed by their names.There are several kinds of variables in SMBX.\kerning0\par
\cf0\b 2.a.2 Kinds of Variables\par
\b0 There are local variables, global variables and system variables in SMBX.They are different in uses, ranges, and 'life spans'.\par
\b 2.a.3 Types\par
\b0 There are mainly two types for variables in SMBX - Double and String(used by some system functions).\par
Values of string type variables are written in quotation marks, for example,\cf2\b\i "a string"\cf0\b0\i0 .\par
Some system functions have used another type of variables - Name.\par
Name stands for a name of something, you do not need quotation marks to express their values.\b\par
2.a.4 Variables Naming Standard\par
\b0 Names of variables can only be numbers, letters and combinations of them.Variable names are not case sensitive.They can not have any spaces.\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 2.b\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\fs22 2.b.1 Local Variables\par
\b0 You can define local variables in Level Editor.Local variables are only affective in the level they are defined.They are Double type(IEEE 64-bit 8-bytes,-1.79769313486232\f2\lang2052\'a1\'c1\f0\lang1033 10\super 308\nosupersub  to -4.94065645841247\f2\lang2052\'a1\'c1\f0\lang1033 10\super -324 \nosupersub for negative values,4.94065645841247\f2\lang2052\'a1\'c1\f0\lang1033 10\super -324\nosupersub  to 1.79769313486232\f2\lang2052\'a1\'c1\f0\lang1033 10\super 308 \nosupersub for positive values) variables.\par
\par
You can control(=read and write) local variables using events and scripts,specially,local variables can be used directly in Messages in events.\par
\par
\b 2.b.2 Global Variables\par
\b0 You can define global variables in World Editor.Global variables are affective in the whole world.They are also Double type variables like local ones.\par
\par
You can only fully control global variables using scripts,but you can still get the values of them with events.\par
\par
When you define a local/global variable,you also defined a String type local/global variable with the same name!For the use of this string type variable, we will explain later.\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 2.c\fs22\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\b0 For the built-in variables, there are system variables and game data variables.Their values will change automatically.The types and ranges are different from one to another.\par
\par
System variables, for example, 1-ups, coins, score, number of NPCs in a level, are read-only variables.Their values are updated as the game runs.\par
\par
Game data variables are sets of complex variables, which can only be accessed through scripts.Datas stored in NPCs,blocks and players belong to this type.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs32 3.Expressions\b0\fs22\par
\b\fs28 3.a\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\fs22 3.a.1 Mathematical Expressions\par
\b0 Mathematical expressions are made up by mathematical symbols and functions,they will return a number after calculation.\par
\par
Mathematical symbols supported by the game:\par
[+] plus,eg: 1+1=2\par
[-] minus,eg: 2-1=1\par
[*] multiplication,eg: 3*4=12\par
[/] division,eg: 5/4=1.25\par
[\\] divide with no remainder,eg: 6\\4=1\par
[^] power,eg: 2^3=8\par
[mod] get the remainder,eg: 3 mod 2=1\par
[()] brackets,to adjust the order of computation,eg: 2*(1+3)=8\par
[&] linking symbol,eg: 1&2=12\par
\par
The game also supports many kinds of functions, including mathematical functions,system functions and custom functions.We only explain the uses of mathematical functions here.\par
[abs] returns the absolute value of the parameter,eg: abs(-1)=1\par
[atn] returns the arctangent value,eg: 4*atn(1)=3.141592654...\par
[cos] returns the cosine value,eg:  cos(3.1415926)=-1\par
[exp] returns the power of e,eg: exp(4) is equal to e^4\par
[fix] rounds the parameter,eg: fix(4.44)=4\f2\lang2052\'a3\'ac\f0\lang1033 fix(-4.44)=-4\par
[int] rounds the parameter,eg: int(4.44)=4\f2\lang2052\'a3\'ac\f0\lang1033 int(-4.44)=-5\par
[log] return the natural logarithm value,eg: log(e)=1\par
[sgn] get the sign of the parameter,eg: sgn(5)=1\f2\lang2052\'a3\'ac\f0\lang1033 sgn(-5)=-1\par
[sin] returns the sine value,eg: sin(3.1415926)=0\par
[sqr] returns the square root,eg: sqr(2) is equal to 2^0.5\par
[tan] returns the tangent value,eg: tan(3.1415926)=0\par
[rnd] returns a random value between 0 and 1, has no parameters, can be used directly,eg: 4*rnd\par
*Use radians in trigonometric functions.\par
\par
\b 3.a.2 Assignment\par
\b0 The assignment is to send the result of an expression to a variable.\par
\par
Use:variable=expression\par
\par
Example:val(a)=cos(2)+3+sgn(4)+rnd*5+log(6)\par
\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 3.b\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\b0\fs22 Logical expression are made up by mathematical expressions and logical symbols.They will tell you if the expressions are true.\par
You will get 0(=false) or 1(=true) after calculations.\par
\par
There are two types of logical symbols: comparing operators and logical operators.The game will calculate comparing operators first.\par
\par
Comparing operators supported by the game:\par
[=] equal,eg: 1=1 returns 1(=true), 1=0 returns 0(=false)\par
[>] greater than,eg: 1>0 returns 1, 1>2 returns 0\par
[<] less than,eg: 1<2 returns 1, 1<0 returns 0\par
[<>] not equal,eg: 1<>2 returns 1, 1<>1 returns 0\par
[>=] not less than,eg: 1>=1 returns 1, 1>=2 returns 0\par
[<=] not greater than,eg: 1<=1 returns 1,1<=0 returns 0\par
\par
Logical operators supported by the game:\par
Unitary operator:[not]\par
