\pard\widctlpar\li840\par
Logical expressions are commonly used in 'If' statements,you can also use them to set the value of variables,of course.\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 3.c\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\b0\fs22 You can also use expressions in events, and all mathematical functions and symbols mentioned above are supported in events.But there is a big limit in other functions and special variables in events.Only the following variables are supported in events, they can be used in the same way in scripts.\par
\par
[val]or[v]:local variables\par
[gval]or[gv]:global variables(ReadOnly)\par
[lvltimer]:the game timer(ReadOnly)\par
[sysval]:system variables(ReadOnly)\par
\par
Messages in events can include local variables,as for the use,input &val(*variable name*).\par
Example:you need &val(a) stars to enter.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs32 4.Control Flow\b0\fs22\par
\b\fs28 4.a\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\b0\fs22 'If' statements will execute expressions if given condition expressions return true.\par
Use:\par
\cf3\b If\cf0\b0  \cf4\i condition \cf3\b\i0 Then\cf0\b0\par
[statement]\par
[\cf3\b Elseif\cf0\b0  \cf4\i condition-n\cf0\i0  \cf3\b Then\cf0\b0 ]\par
[statement]\par
[\cf3\b Else\cf0\b0 ]\par
[statement]\par
\cf3\b End If\par
\cf0\b0\par
Things in '[]' is optional.'Condition' means a logical expression.\par
Multiple 'Elseif' can exist in a 'If' statement, but only one for 'Else'.\par
\par
If 'condition' returns true,the game will execute the following statement and then jump to 'End If' to execute other statements.\par
\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 4.b\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\b0\fs22 'Select Case' statements will select one of the given statements according to the result of the test-expression.\par
Use:\par
\cf3\b Select Case\cf0\b0  \cf4\i test-expression\cf0\i0\par
\cf3\b Case\cf0\b0  \cf4\i experssion\cf0\i0\par
[statement]\par
[\cf3\b Case\cf0\b0  \cf4\i expression-n\cf0\i0 ]\par
[statement]\par
[\cf3\b Case Else\cf0\b0 ]\par
[statement]\par
\cf3\b End Select\par
\cf0\b0\par
Things in '[]' is optional.'Expression' is a mathematical expression.\par
Multiple 'Case' can exist in a 'Select Case' statement, but only one for 'Case Else'.\par
\par
The game will first calculate the 'test-expression' and get the return value, then search for the expressions following 'Case' which returns the same value.Once the expression is found, the game will immediately execute the statements following it and jump to 'End Select' to execute other statements.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 4.c\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\b0\fs22 'For' statements repeat executing a set of statements for certain times.\par
Use:\par
\cf3\b For\cf0\b0  \cf4\i counter\cf0\i0  = \cf4\i start\cf0\i0  \cf3\b To\cf0\b0  \cf4\i End\cf0\i0  [\cf3\b Step\cf0\b0  \cf4\i step\cf0\i0 ]\par
[statement]\par
[\cf3\b Exit For\cf0\b0 ]\par
\cf3\b Next\par
\cf0\b0\par
Things in '[]' is optional.'Counter' is a local variable.'Start','end','step' are mathematical expressions.'Exit For' can exist in the statements with an unlimited number.When 'Exit For' is executed, the game will jump to 'Next' to execute other statements outside 'For' statements.\par
\par
The 'step' is defaultly set to 1 if ignored.\par
\par
When the 'For' statements are executed, the game will send the value of 'start' to the local variable 'counter'.Then 'statement' is executed.When the calculation reaches 'Next', the game will add the step value to 'counter' and compare the 'counter' variable to 'End'.If the value of the 'counter' is greater than 'End',the game will jump to 'Next' and continue execute statements after 'Next', or the game will repeat executing statements inside the 'For' statement.\par
\par
Here is an example:\par
\cf3\b For\cf0\b0  \cf3\b val\cf0\b0 (a) = 1 \cf3\b To\cf0\b0  10 \cf3\b Step\cf0\b0  2\par
  \cf3\b If val\cf0\b0 (a) = 5 \cf3\b Then\par
\cf0\b0     \cf3\b Exit For\par
\cf0\b0   \cf3\b End If\par
Next\par
\par
\cf0\b0\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 4.d\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\b0\fs22 'Do' statements repeat executing the statements inside them.\par
Use:\par
\par
\cf3\b Do \cf0\b0 [\{\cf3\b While\cf0\b0 |\cf3\b Until\cf0\b0\} \cf4\i condition\cf0\i0 ]\cf3\b\par
\cf0\b0 [statement]\par
[\cf3\b Exit Do\cf0\b0 ]\par
\cf3\b Loop\cf0\b0  [\{\cf3\b While\cf0\b0 |\cf3\b Until\cf0\b0\} \cf4\i condition\cf0\i0 ]\par
\par
You can only choose one '[]',either the one following 'Do' or the one following 'Loop', and only one key word in the '[]','While' or 'Until'.'Condition' is a logical expression..'Exit Do' can exist in the statements with an unlimited number.When 'Exit Do' is executed, the game will jump to 'Loop' to execute other statements outside 'Do' expressions.\par
\par
If 'While' key word is chosen, the game will repeat executing the statements inside the 'Do' statements until 'condition' returns true.\par
If 'Until' key word is chosen, the game will repeat executing the statements inside the 'Do' statements until 'condition' returns false.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 4.e\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\b0\fs22 'With' statements apply a set of statements to a given object.\par
Use:\par
\cf3\b With\cf0\b0  \cf4\i object\cf0\i0\par
[statement]\par
\cf3\b End With\par
\cf0\b0\par
'Object' means an object in the game.Here is an example:\par
\cf3\b With\cf0\b0  npc(1)\par
.x = 12345\par
.y = 54321\par
\cf3\b End With\par
\cf0\b0\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 4.f\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\b0\fs22 'Goto' statements,when they are executed, will force the calculation to jump to a given line of the script.\par
\cf3\b Goto\cf0\b0  \cf4\i line\cf0\i0\par
\par
'Line' is a name of a label.Labels are made in the following way:\par
\cf4\i line:\cf0\i0\par
Label names should not consist of symbols that should not exist in variables.There should also not be two labels with the same name in a single script.You can not use 'Goto' statements inter-functionally.There should not be 'Goto' statements inside 'With' statements,either.\par
\par
Here is an example of endless looping(avoid these things in your scripts):\par
endless:\par
\cf3\b val\cf0\b0 (a) = 1\par
\cf3\b Goto\cf0\b0  endless\par
\par
'Gosub' statements is an alternative version of 'Goto' statements but with some differences. When they are executed, the program will also be forced to jump to a given line. What makes it differ from 'Goto' statements is that a 'return' statement can be followed after it. When the 'return' statement is executed, the program will return to the next line of the corresponding 'Gosub' statement and continue executing. If a 'return' statement occurred without a 'Gosub' statement, it will be ignored. Like 'Goto' statements, 'Gosub' statements can not be used in 'with' blocks, nor can it be used inter-functionally, and if a script or a function exits without exiting all 'gosub' statements, the return stack in the current structure will be cleared. 'Gosub' statements will not affect the usablility of 'sleep' functions therefore 'sleep' functions can be used within sub procedures, and in this situation the return stack will not be cleared.\par
\par
\cf3\b Gosub\cf0\b0  \cf4\i line\cf0\i0\par
\par
Here is a example using 'gosub' statements to iterate.\par
mysub:\par
\cf3\b val\cf0\b0 (a) = \cf3\b val\cf0\b0 (a) + 1\par
\cf3\b If val\cf0\b0 (a) < 10 \cf3\b Then\cf0\b0\par
\cf3\b Gosub\cf0\b0  mysub\par
\cf3\b End If\cf0\b0\par
\cf3\b Return\cf0\b0\par
\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs32 5.Functions and Procedures\b0\fs22\par
\b\fs28 5.a\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840\b0\fs22 Here are some examples using functions and procedures.\par
\cf3\b Call\cf0\b0  LSet(LayerA,0,1)\par
\cf3\b Call\cf0\b0  NKill(getID(\cf3\b val\cf0\b0 (a)),0,0,0,0,0,1,1)\par
\cf3\b val\cf0\b0 (a) = NCreate(1,\cf3\b val\cf0\b0 (b),\cf3\b val\cf0\b0 (c),0,0,0,0)\par
\cf3\b Call\cf0\b0  ShowMsg(\cf2\b\i "You need "\cf0\b0\i0  & CStr(\cf3\b val\cf0\b0 (c)) & \cf2\b\i " stars to enter."\cf0\b0\i0 )\par
\par
[LMove]\par
LMove(\cf4\i layername\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i px\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i py\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i type\cf0\i0 )\par
To move a layer.\par
layername (Layer) Name of the layer you want to move.\par
px(Double) x-axis parameter of the movement.\{Speed|Relative Shift\}\par
py(Double) y-axis parameter of the movement.\{Speed|Relative Shift\}\par
type(Double) Moving style.Set it to 0 to move layers with the given speeds,set it to 1 to move layers with the given relative shifts.\par
When used in global scripts, this function will affect the layers in your world map.\par
\par
[LSet]\par
LSet(\cf4\i layername\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i type\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i advset\cf0\i0 )\par
To change the visiblity of a layer.\par
layername (Layer) Layer name.\par
type(Double) Style,1 = Show,2 = Hide,3 = Toggle\par
advset(Double) Whether smoke effects are shown,set to 0 to show them,set to values other than 0 to stop them from showing.\par
When used in global scripts, this function will affect the layers in your world map.\cf5\i\par
\cf6\fs16 Specially, you can modify the transparency of the layers by setting the 'type' parameter to 38. In this case the advset would be an integer between 0 and 255, which stands for the transparency. The transparency settings will affect blocks, NPCs and backgrounds but will NOT affect the layers in world maps.\par
\cf0\i0\fs22\par
[LSpin]\par
LSpin(\cf4\i layername\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i cx\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i cy\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i aspeed\cf0\i0 )\par
To rotate a layer.\par
layername (Layer) Layer name.\par
cx (Double) the x-position of the rotation center\par
cy (Double) the y-position of the rotation center\par
aspeed(Double) the angular speed of the rotation, set to 0 to reset the rotation process\par
When used in global scripts, this function will affect the layers in your world map.\par
This function only affects NPCs and Blocks.\par
\par
[ShowMsg]\par
ShowMsg(\cf4\i string\cf0\i0 )\par
To show a message box.\par
string(String) Messages shown.\par
\par
[FXCreate]\par
FXCreate(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i x\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i y\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i sx\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i sy\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i f\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i fs\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i fc\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i ng\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i advset\cf0\i0 )\par
To create an effect\par
id(Double) Effect ID\par
x(Double) x-position of the effect\par
y(Double) y-position of the effect\par
sx(Double) x-axis speed of the effect\par
sy(Double) y-axis speed of the effect\par
f(Double) determines how many frames the effect will last\par
fs(Double) determines how fast the effect animation plays\par
fc(Double) playing const of the effect.Default value is 0.\par
ng(Double) set this to 0 to enable the gravity for the effect,set this to a value other than 0 to disable it.\par
advset(Double) extra data for the effect.Default value is 0.\par
\par
[TCreate]\par
TCreate(\cf4\i eventname\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i delay\cf0\i0 )\par
To create a event timer.\par
eventname(Event) The name of the event to be triggered\par
delay(Double) frames to wait\par
\par
[PlayNote]\par
PlayNote(\cf4\i command\cf0\i0 )\par
To play a note.\par
command(Double) send a command to the sound card to make it play a note or set the playing mode.\par
\par
The 'command' can be:\par
To change the instrument:\cf4\i Patch\cf0\i0  * 256 + 192 + \cf4\i Channel\cf0\i0\par
To play a note:\cf4\i Volume\cf0\i0  * 65536 + \cf4\i Flip\cf0\i0  * 256 + 144 + \cf4\i Channel\cf0\i0\par
To stop the playing note:\cf4\i Volume\cf0\i0  * 65536 + \cf4\i Flip\cf0\i0  * 256 + 128 + \cf4\i Channel\cf0\i0\par
Volume stands for how loud the note played.Range:0-100\par
Flip stands for the pitch of the note.Range:0-255\par
Channel stands for the channel the note plays in.Range:0-15(Default:0)\par
Patch stands for the ID of instruments.Range:0-127\par
\par
[Sleep]\par
Sleep(\cf4\i delay\cf0\i0 )\par
Temporary stops the script from further executing for a short time.\par
delay(Double) sets the number of frames delayed\par
\par
You can \cf7\b only \cf0\b0 use this in scripts triggered by events, not in custom functions and procedures.\par
\par
[TClear]\par
TClear(\cf4\i type\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i eventname\cf0\i0 )\par
To delete a event timer.\par
type(Double) clear type.Set this to 1 to clear all activated event timers.Set this to 0 to clear only the timer of the given event\par
eventname(Event) to set the event name if clear type is set to 0\par
\par
[EXEScript]\par
EXEScript(\cf4\i scriptname\cf0\i0 )\par
To execute a local/global script.\par
scriptname(Script) the name of the script to be executed.\par
When this function is called, the given script will immediately be executed and the original script will be halted until the execution of the given script completes.\par
\par
[Debug]\par
Debug(\cf4\i string\cf0\i0 )\par
To output texts to the debugger.\par
string(String) the string to be outputted.\par
If the level is tested in the editor, this function will output the information in the string to the debug window in Debugger, otherwise it won't do anything. However, for better game performance, you should delete all 'Debug' functions after debugging.\par
\par
[HUDSet]\par
HUDSet(\cf4\i command\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i p1\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i p2\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i p3\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i p4\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i p5\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i p6\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i p7\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i p8\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i p9\cf0\i0 )\par
To modify the HUD (short for 'head-up display'). This is a compacted function with its effect varying form the parameter 'command'.\par
Parameter p1, p2, p3, ... ,p9 are all double type parameters which have different meanings according to the parameter 'command'.\par
command(String) the command to be executed and it can be:\par
1) "\cf8 initialize\cf0 ": all parameters are not used for this command and should be 0. This command will forcefully initialize the HUD system and erases all the previous custom HUD data.\par
2) "\cf8 destroy\cf0 ": all parameters are not used for this command and should be 0. This command will disable the custom HUD system and erases all the previous custom HUD data.\par
3) "\cf8 bitmap\cf0 ": to add a bitmap to the HUD. Uses '\cf7\b scflash.png\cf0\b0 ' as the bitmap source. The function is used in this way.\par
HUDSet("bitmap", id, sx, sy, sw, sh, dx, dy, advset, color)\par
id(Double/Int32) stands for the exclusive ID of the bitmap. The function will create a new bitmap if the ID is unused, otherwise it will overwrite the existing bitmap.\par
sx(Double/Int32) stands for the x-position of the left-top point in the bitmap source file\par
sy(Double/Int32) stands for the y-position of the left-top point in the bitmap source file\par
sw(Double/Int32) stands for the width of the cropped bitmap\par
sh(Double/Int32) stands for the height of the cropped bitmap\par
dx(Double/Int32) stands for the x-position of the destination point on the screen. The left-top point of the screen has a x-position of 0.\par
dy(Double/Int32) stands for the y-position of the destination point on the screen. The left-top point of the screen has a y-position of 0.\par
advset(Double/Int32) advanced settings. Can be one of these values:\par
\cf5\i\fs16 1000 to 1000+NPCNum : shows the image of the NPC with a type ID of [advset-1000]\par
5001 : shows the image of the NPC in player one's item box\par
5002 : shows the image of the NPC in player two's item box\par
6001 to 6003 : if the [advset-6000]th starcoin has been acquired then the bitmap will be normally drawn, or it won't be drawn.\par
\cf0\i0\fs22 If the advset is set to a valid value, the parameter sx and sy will be unused and the parameter sw and sh will become the stretch ratios of the bitmap drawn. For example, \cf5\i if advset is set to 5001 or 5002 and sw, sh set to 1, the size of the drawn bitmap will be 32*32.\par
\cf0\i0 color(Double/Int32) stands for a certain color. The default value is -1 and type 0 to make the bitmap completely transparent.\par
4) "\cf8 text\cf0 :\cf9\b *\cf0\b0 " :to add a text to the custom HUD. [\cf9\b *\cf0\b0 ] can be any valid strings to be displayed. This function uses a NPC as the font. The function is now used in this way:\par
HUDSet("text:\cf9\b *\cf0\b0 ", id, dx, dy, startasc, endasc, lnum, npcid, color, -1)\par
id(Double/Int32) stands for the only ID of the text created. The function will create a new text if the ID is unused, otherwise it will overwrite the existing text.\par
dx(Double/Int32) stands for the x-position of the text. The left-top point of the screen has a x-position of 0.\par
dy(Double/Int32) stands for the y-position of the text. The left-top point of the screen has a y-position of 0.\par
startasc(Double/In32): the beginning ASCII code of the NPC image font.\par
endasc(Double/In32): the last ASCII code of the NPC image font.\par
lnum(Double/In32): the number of characters of a single row in the NPC image file.\par
npcid(Double/In32): ID of the NPC used as the font.Use the numbers in the NPC image filename as the ID.\par
color(Double/Int32) stands for a certain color. The default value is -1 and type 0 to make the text completely transparent.\par
\par
[TxtCreate]\par
TxtCreate(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i x\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i y\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i sasc\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i easc\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i cdata\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i lnum\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i fontid\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i flag\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i text\cf0\i0 )\par
To show a piece of text using the image of an NPC as the font.\par
id(Double/Int32): the only ID of the text object created.\par
x(Double/In32): x-position of the text\par
y(Double/In32): y-position of the text\par
sasc(Double/In32): the beginning ASCII code of the NPC image font.\par
easc(Double/In32): the last ASCII code of the NPC image font.\par
cdata(Double/In32): reserved.Type 0.\par
lnum(Double/In32): the number of characters of a single row in the NPC image file.\par
fontid(Double/In32): ID of the NPC used as the font.Use the numbers in the NPC image filename as the ID.\par
flag(Double/In32): Set this to 0 and the coordinate will be oriented to the level coordinate system.Set this to 1 and it will be oriented to the screen.\par
text(String): the text shown.\par
\par
[BmpCreate]\par
BmpCreate(\cf4\i id\cf0 ,\cf4  picid\cf0 ,\cf4  flagA\cf0 ,\cf4  flagB\cf0 ,\cf4  sx\cf0 ,\cf4  sy\cf0 ,\cf4  sw\cf0 ,\cf4  sh\cf0 ,\cf4  dx\cf0 ,\cf4  dy\cf0 ,\cf4  scx\cf0 ,\cf4  scy\cf0 ,\cf4  pcx\cf0 ,\cf4  pcy\cf0 ,\cf4  angle\cf0 ,\cf4  color\cf0\i0 )\par
To create a highly customable bitmap object. Needs a NPC as the bitmap source.\par
ID(Double/Int32): stands for the only ID of the bitmap object. The function will create a new bitmap if the ID is unused, otherwise nothing will happen.\par
picid(Double/Int32): ID of the NPC used as the bitmap source.Use the numbers in the NPC image filename as the ID.\par
flagA(Double/Bool): Set this to 0 and the coordinate will be oriented to the level coordinate system.Set this to 1 and it will be oriented to the screen.\par
flagB(Double/Bool): Set this to 0 and the bitmap created will be hidden. Set this to 1 and the bitmap will be visible.\par
sx(Double/Int32): stands for the x-position of the left-top point in the bitmap source file\par
sy(Double/Int32): stands for the y-position of the left-top point in the bitmap source file\par
sw(Double/Int32): stands for the width of the cropped bitmap\par
sh(Double/Int32): stands for the height of the cropped bitmap\par
dx(Double/Int32): stands for the x-position of the bitmap shown.\par
dy(Double/Int32): stands for the y-position of the bitmap shown.\par
scx(Double): stands for the x-axis stretch ratio. Default value is 1.\par
scy(Double): stands for the y-axis stretch ratio. Default value is 1.\par
pcx(Double/Int32): stands for the x-position of the center point used in stretch and rotation.\par
pcy(Double/Int32): stands for the y-position of the center point used in stretch and rotation.\par
angle(Double): stands for the rotation angle of the bitmap.\par
color(Double/Int32) stands for a certain color. The default value is -1 and type 0 to make the image completely transparent.\par
\cf10\i Warning: Performance issues may occur if too many bitmaps are created and the game will crash if the area represented by sx, sy, sw, sh is not valid. Use this function with caution! Don't use it in the way as you do with NPCs!\par
\cf0\i0\par
[BErase]\par
BErase(\cf4\i type\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i id\cf0\i0 )\par
To destroy a bitmap object or text object.\par
type(Double/Int32) the object type, set this to 0 to destroy an iterator object, set this to 1 to destroy a text object and 2 for a bitmap object.\f2  \par
\f0 ID(Double/Int32)  the exclusive ID of the object to be destroyed. The function will do nothing if the object is not found.\par
\cf5\i If you are just going to hide the object, modify the 'hide' property instead of using this function.\par
\par
\cf0\i0 [TCreateEx]\par
TCreateEx(\cf4\i Scriptname, Timer, Par1, Par2, Par3\cf0\i0 )\par
To execute a local/global script after certain frames and pass parameters to the script.\par
Scriptname(Script): the script to be executed.\par
Timer(Doubule/Int32): frames to wait.\par
Par1(Double/Int32): the value to be passed to Sysval(Param1)\par
Par2(Double/Int32): the value to be passed to Sysval(Param2)\par
Par3(Double/Int32): the value to be passed to Sysval(Param3)\par
\cf5\i\par
\cf0\i0 [AudioSet]\par
AudioSet(\cf4\i Op, Sid, Par, Filepath\cf0\i0 )\par
To control the sound effects and music of the game.\par
Op(Double/Int32): the command to be executed, can be one of the following values:\par
1: load sound effect\par
Sid(Double/Int32): sound effect ID. The valid range is 1 to 1024.\par
Par(Double/Int32): whether only one 'copy' of this sound effect can be played in the same time.\par
Filepath(String): the file name of the sound effect. The sound file should be placed in the world map folder.\par
2: play sound effect\par
Sid(Double/Int32): sound effect ID. The valid range is 1 to 1024.\par
Other parameters are unused, set them to 0 or an empty string for Filepath.\par
3: stop sound effect\par
Sid(Double/Int32): sound effect ID. The valid range is 1 to 1024.\par
Other parameters are unused, set them to 0 or an empty string for Filepath.\par
11: play music\par
Sid(Double/Int32): duration (in milliseconds) of the fade-in effect.\par
Filepath(String): the file name of the music. The music file should be placed in the world map folder.\par
Other parameters are unused, set them to 0.\par
12: stop music\par
Sid(Double/Int32): duration (in milliseconds) of the fade-out effect.\par
Other parameters are unused, set them to 0 or an empty string for Filepath.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 5.b\par

\pard\widctlpar\li852\b0\fs22 Functions can be parts of mathematical functions.\par
\par
[round]\par
Round(\cf4\i expression\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i numdecimalplaces\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns a double type value.This function rounds the value inputted.You can specify how many digits after the decimal dot remaining.\par
expression(Double) the expression you want to round the result value\par
numdecimalplaces(Double) number of digits remaining after the decimal dot\par
\par
[len]\par
Len(\cf4\i string\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns a double type value,telling the length of the string.\par
string(String) the string to get the length of\par
\par
[left]\par
Left(\cf4\i string\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i length\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns a string which is cropped from the string inputted.The result string begins from the beginning of the original one and has a limited length.\par
string(String) the original string to be cropped\par
length(Double) the length of the result string\par
\par
[right]\par
Right(\cf4\i string\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i length\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns a string which is cropped from the string inputted.The result string begins from the end of the original one and has a limited length.\par
string(String) the original string to be cropped\par
length(Double) the length of the result string\par
\par
[mid]\par
Mid(\cf4\i string\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i start\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i length\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns a string which is cropped from the string inputted.The result string begins from a definite point of the original one and has a limited length.\par
string(String) the original string to be cropped\par
start(Double) the start point of the original string\par
length(Double) the length of the cropped string\par
\par
[replace]\par
Replace(\cf4\i expression\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i find\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i replacewith\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i start\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i count\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i compare\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns a string with some parts of the original string replaced by new parts.You can define the parts to be searched for in the original string,and the maximum times of the replacement.\par
expression(String) the original string\par
find(String) the parts of the original string to be searched and replaced\par
replacewith(String) the new string parts used to replace\par
start(Double) the start point of the search\par
count(Double) times of the replacement.Set this to -1 to disable this limit.\par
compare(Double) can be 0 or 1.Set this to 0 to make the search case sensitive\par
\par
[chr], [chrW]\par
Chr(\cf4\i charcode\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns a string containing a character with the specified code.\par
charcode(Double) the code of the character\par
\par
[asc], [ascW]\par
Asc(\cf4\i string\cf0\i0 )\par
To get the character code of the first character in the given string.Returns type double.\par
string(String) can be any valid strings\par
\par
[cstr]\par
CStr(\cf4\i expression\cf0\i0 )\par
To convert a number(double type) to string type.\par
expression(Double) can be any valid expressions returning a number\par
\par
[cdbl]\par
CDbl(\cf4\i expression\cf0\i0 )\par
To convert a string to a double type number.\par
expression(String) can be any valid strings\par
\par
[instr]\par
InStr(\cf4\i start\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i string1\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i string2\cf0\i0 )\par
To return the point of the first appearance of a given string in another string.\par
start(Double) to specify the start point of the search\par
string1(String) the original string\par
string2(String) the string to be searched\par
\par
[NCreate]\par

\pard\widctlpar\li840 NCreate(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i x\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i y\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i sx\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i sy\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i advset\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i cdata\cf0\i0 )\par

\pard\widctlpar\li852 Returns the permanent ID(double type) of the NPC created.\par
id(Double)  type-ID of the NPC , eg: 1 for a goomba\par
x(Double)  x-position of the NPC\par
y(Double)  y-position of the NPC\par
sx(Double)  x-axis speed of the NPC\par
sy(Double) x-axis speed of the NPC\par
advset(Double) additional data of the NPC.Default:0\par
cdata(Double) creation information.Default:0\par
\par
The permanent ID returned will become effective in the next frame of the creation.The NPC is not really created immediately in the frame the script is executed.\par
\par
Specially, when the parameter id is set to -1, the parameter advset can be set to the permanent ID of an NPC, and this function will duplicate the NPC. If the source NPC is a legacy style NPC generator, this function will create a duplicated NPC with generator effects. If the source NPC does not exist, nothing will be done.\par
\par
[NKill]\par
NKill(\cf4\i index\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i rx\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i ry\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i rw\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i rh\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i id\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i effect\cf0\i0 , \cf4\i score\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns the number of NPCs deleted.\par
index(Double) Deletion style.If this value is greater than 0,this value will stand for the NPC type-ID.If this value is 0, the function will delete the specified NPC.If this value is -1, this function will delete all NPCs touching a rectangular box.If this value is -2, this function will delete all NPCs fully in a rectangular box.\par
rx(Double) the x-position of the rectangular box.If 'index' is not -1 or -2,type 0.\par
ry(Double) the y-position of the rectangular box.If 'index' is not -1 or -2,type 0.\par
rw(Double) the width of the rectangular box.If 'index' is not -1 or -2,type 0.\par
rh(Double) the height of the rectangular box.If 'index' is not -1 or -2,type 0.\par
id(Double) If 'index' is -1 or -2,this stands for the ID of the NPCs to delete.Set this to 0 to delete all NPCs.If 'index' is not -1 or -2,type 0.\par
effect(Double) to determine whether the dying effects are shown.Set this to 0 to disable the effects.Set this to any number other than 0 to show them.\par
score(Double) to determine whether players can get score from the delection.Set this to 0 to disable the scoring.Set this to any number other than 0 to enable the scoring.\par
\par
[getID]\par
getID(\cf4\i permid\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns a double type variable stands for the NPC ID using a permanent ID.\par
permid(Double) the permanent ID\par
\par
[getIDByName]\par
getIDByName(\cf4\i\f1 Name\cf0\i0 )\par
To find the object with the given name. Returns the object ID.\par
Name(String) the name of the object to be found\par
\par
[ItrCreate]\par
ItrCreate(\cf4\i type, id, x, y, w, h\cf0\i0 )\par
To create an iterator which can be used to quickly iterate through all IDs of objects that satisfy a certain condition. Returns the ID of the iterator created. Returns 0 if this function failed. Use BErase to destroy an iterator.\par
type(Double) the type of objects to be iterated. 1 for blocks, 2 for NPCs, 3 for background objects, 11 for blocks on the current screen, 12 for activate NPCs.\par
id(Double) ID filter of the iterator, set this to 0 for no ID filtering, or the iterator only iterate through objects with the same image file ID.\par
x(Double) x-position of the range filter, the iterator only iterate through objects within the given rectangular region.\par
y(Double) y-position of the range filter, the iterator only iterate through objects within the given rectangular region.\par
w(Double) width of the range filter, the iterator only iterate through objects within the given rectangular region.\par
h(Double) height of the range filter, the iterator only iterate through objects within the given rectangular region.\cf7\f2\par
\cf0\f0\par
\f1 [ItrNext]\par
ItrNext(\cf4\i ItrID\cf0\i0 )\par
To get the next object of the iterator. Returns the object ID. If the object does not exist, the return value will be 0 and the iterator will be destoryed.\par
ItrID(Double) ID of the iterator. If the iterator does not exist or the iteration has been ended, the function will return 0.\par
\f0\par
[sysval]\par
sysval(\cf4\i cname\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns the value of a system variable.\par
cname(Name) the name of the system variable.\par
\par
\f1 The 'cname' can be:\par
NCount stands for the number of NPCs existing.\par
BCount stands for the number of blocks existing.\par
BGOCount stands for then number of background objects existing.\par
WCount stands for the number of warps existing.\par
LCount stands for the number of liquids existing.\par
GameMode stands for the current game mode. 0 means single player mode, 1 means two player mode, 2 means battle mode.\par
ScrSplitstyle stands for the screen splitting status.\par
\f0 Player1scrX stands for the left-top x-position of the camera for player1.\par
Player1scrY stands for the left-top y-position of the camera for player1.\par
Player2scrX stands for the left-top x-position of the camera for player2.\par
Player2scrY stands for the left-top y-position of the camera for player2.\par
WldInvCount stands for how many items are there in the world map inventory.\cf7\par
\cf0 Playerhealth(Writable) stands for the current 1up number.\par
CoinCount(Writable) stands for the coins number.\par
Score(Writable) stands for the current score.\par
StarCount stands for the current star number.\par
Param1 stands for the first parameter transmitted from events.\par
Param2 stands for the second parameter transmitted from events.\par
\f1 Param3 stands \f0 for the \f2 third\f0  parameter transmitted from events.\par
BPlayer1Health stands for the 1-up number of the first player in battle mode.\par
BPlayer2Health stands for the 1-up number of the first player in battle mode.\par
EnableLighting(WriteOnly) stands for the state of the light system.\par
Starcoincount stands for the number of acquired star coins.\par
Disablesave(WriteOnly) stands for whether the player are forbidden to save.\par
\par
When you are using events to execute scripts,'Param1' is the object ID triggering the event, while 'Param2' is the type of the object triggering the event.\par
\par
\cf6\i\fs16 You can use CNPC code [scripts=script name] to attach a script to a type of NPC.The NPC will execute the script once a frame and all original movements of the NPC will be disabled.'Param1' is set to the NPC ID.You can completely control NPCs using this method.This is the third way to use scripts.\par
[Warning]You are not supposed to use this unless you are well-prepared.Crashing is frequently occurred if used in a bad way.\cf0\i0\fs22\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 5.c\par

\pard\widctlpar\li852\b0\fs22 The grammar is:\par
\cf3\b Script\cf0\b0  \cf4\i name\cf0\i0 ([\cf4\i arg\cf0\i0  \cf3\b as type\cf0\b0 ],......,[\cf3\b return type\cf0\b0 ])\par
[statement]\par
\cf3\b End Script\cf0\b0\par
\par
'Name' is the name of the function/procedure.\par
'Arg' is the name of the arguments.\par
'Type' can be double or string.\par
There can only be one or zero 'return'.If there is not a 'return',the 'script' will be a procedure, or it will be a function.\par
The number of arguments is not limited. \par
\par
If it is a function, you can use the following code to define the return value of your function.\par
\cf3\b return\cf0\b0  \cf4\i expression\cf0\i0\par
\par
To use the arguments in custom functions/procedures, input the following codes.\par
[Param]\par
Param(\cf4\i pname\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns the value of the double type argument with the name of 'pname'.\par
pname(Name) the name of the argument\par
\par
[strParam]\par
strParam(\cf4\i pname\cf0\i0 )\par
Returns the value of the string type argument with the name of 'pname'.\par
pname(Name) the name of the argument\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs32 6.Errors\b0\fs22\par
\b\fs28 6.a\par

\pard\widctlpar\li852\b0\fs22 There are two types of errors in scripts - compiling errors and runtime errors.\par
\par
If a script of a level have compiling errors itself,the game will report the error with a pop-up window.All scripts with errors will not be executed.\par
\par
If a script has invalid parameters and other 'hidden' errors,the game will crash if the error is triggered when playing the level.This is called a runtime error.Further information about runtime errors can be found in Visual Basic documents.\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs28 6.b\par

\pard\widctlpar\li852\b0\fs22 These are error codes of compiling errors.\par
\i 0--Syntax error in the expression.\par
1--Syntax error in the code block.\par
2--Cannot use 'Goto' statements inside 'With' blocks.\par
3--Error in the SELECT statement:'Case' expected.\par
4--Error in the SELECT statement:Invalid expression.\par
5--Error in the SELECT statement:Blank 'Case' block.\par
6--Error in the FOR statement:Initial variable not set.\par
7--Error in the FOR statement:'For' expected.\par
8--Error in the DO statement:Format error.\par
9--Error in the WITH statement:Invalid object directed.\par
10--Error in the GOTO statement:Label not found.\par
11--Error in the custom function:Invalid parameters.\par
12--Invalid expression.\par
13--Syntax error in the variable assignment.\par
14--Type error in the variable assignment.\par
15--Error in the custom function:Function not found.\par
16--Error in the custom function:Invalid definition.\par
17--Error in the custom function:Invalid return values.\par
18--Error in the custom function:Ambiguous expression.\par
19--Syntax error:Expressions between code blocks detected.\par
31--Error in the IF statement:Incomplete expression.\par
32--Error in the SELECT statement:Incomplete expression.\par
33--Error in the WITH statement:Incomplete expression.\par
34--Error in the FOR statement:Incomplete expression.\par
35--Error in the DO statement:Incomplete expression.\par
36--Error in the custom function:Incomplete expression.\par
37--Invalid custom function detected in the logic statements.\par
38--Unknown error.\par
\i0\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs32 Appendix\par
\fs28 1.Game Variable List\b0\fs22\par

\pard\widctlpar\li852 [v] or [val]\par
v(\cf4\i name\cf0\i0 ) or val(\cf4\i name\cf0\i0 )\par
name(Name) the name of the local 'double' type variable variable you want to use\par
\par
[gv] or [gval]\par
gv(\cf4\i name\cf0\i0 ) or gval(\cf4\i name\cf0\i0 )\par
name(Name) the name of the global 'double' type variable you want to use\par
\par
[lvlTimer]\par
lvlTimer(\cf4\i cname\cf0\i0 )\par
cname(Name) a name const of the game timer, stands for a certain property of the timer.\par
\par
The 'cname' can be:\par
Count(Double) stands for the current number of the timer\par
Intv(Double) stands for the number of frames needed for the timer to change\par
Type(Double) stands for the timing mode of the timer\par
Show(Double) stands for whether the timer is shown\par
X(Double) stands for the x-position of the timer\par
Y(Double) stands for the y-position of the timer\par
Color(Double/Int32) stands for the color of the timer\par
\par
[str]\par
str(\cf4\i name\cf0\i0 )\par
name(Name) the name of the local  'string' type variable you want to use\par
\par
[gstr]\par
gstr(\cf4\i name\cf0\i0 )\par
name(Name) the name of the global 'string' type variable you want to use\par
\par
[NPC]\par
NPC(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 ).\cf4\i name\cf0\i0\par
id(Double) ID of the specified NPC\par
name(Name) the property of the specified NPC\par
\par
The 'name' can be:\par
X(Double) stands for the x-position of the NPC\par
Y(Double) stands for the y-position of the NPC\par
prX(Double) stands for the original x-position of the NPC\par
prY(Double) stands for the original y-position of the NPC\par
Xsp(Double) stands for the x-axis speed of the NPC\par
Ysp(Double) stands for the y-axis speed of the NPC\par
ID(Double/Int32) stands for the type ID of the NPC,eg: 10 for a SMB3 coin\par
addvx(Double) stands for the x-axis platform speed of the NPC\par
addvy(Double) stands for the y-axis platform speed of the NPC\par
facing(Double/bool) stands for the facing direction of the NPC\par
friendly(Double/bool) stands for whether the NPC is 'friendly'\par
NoMove(Double/bool) stands for whether the NPC is in 'don't move' state\par
curframe(Double/Int32) stands for the current frame of the NPC\par
health(Double/Int32) stands for the health points of the NPC\par
advSet(Double/Int32) stands for the additional data of the NPC\par
permID(Double+ReadOnly) stands for the permanent ID of the NPC\par
alive(Double/bool) stands for whether the NPC is alive\par
ivala(Double/Int32) stands for the individual variable A of the NPC\par
ivalb(Double/Int32) stands for the individual variable B of the NPC\par
ivalc(Double/Int32) stands for the individual variable C of the NPC\par
Name(String) stands for the name of this object\par
\par
[Block]\par
Block(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 ).\cf4\i name\cf0\i0\par
id(Double) ID of the block\par
name(Name) the property of the specified block\par
\par
The 'name' can be:\par
X(Double) stands for the x-position of the block\par
Y(Double) stands for the y-position of the block\par
Xsp(Double) stands for the x-axis speed of the block\par
Ysp(Double) stands for the y-axis speed of the block\par
ID(Double/Int32) stands for the ID of the block\par
advset(Double/Int32) stands for the ID of the block's content\par
Name(String) stands for the name of this object\par
\par
[Char]\par
Char(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 ).\cf4\i name\cf0\i0\par
id(Double) ID of the player\par
name(Name) the property of the specified player\par
\par
The 'name' can be:\par
X(Double) stands for the x-position of the player\par
Y(Double) stands for the y-position of the player\par
Status(Double/Int16) stands for the current state of the player\par
InvTime(Double) stands for the invincible time left for the player\par
Xsp(Double) stands for the x-axis speed of the player\par
Ysp(Double) stands for the y-axis speed of the player\par
ItemSlot(Double/Int16) stands for the mount player currently has\par
itemRsrv(Double/Int16) stands for the type ID of the NPC reserved in the player's item box.\par
Brightness(Double/Int16) stands for the brightness of the player (used in light system)\par
hitpoint(Double/Int16) stands for the current health of the player if the player is \f1 Peach, Toad or Link\par
facing(Double/Bool) stands for the direction of the player currently facing\par
bombcnt(Double/Int16) stands for the number of bombs the player currently has\par
keycnt(Double/Int16) stands for the number of keys the player currently has\par
fluddcap(Double/Int16) stands for the capacity of player's F.L.U.D.D.\par
\par
[Bgo]\par
Bgo(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 ).\cf4\i name\cf0\i0\par
id(Double) ID of the background object\par
name(Name) the property of the specified background object\par
\par
The 'name' can be:\par
X(Double) stands for the x-position of the background object\par
Y(Double) stands for the y-position of the background object\par
Xsp(Double) stands for the x-axis speed of the background object\par
Ysp(Double) stands for the y-axis speed of the background object\par
ID(Double/Int32) stands for the ID of the background object\par
\par
[Liquid]\par
Liquid(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 ).\cf4\i name\cf0\i0\par
id(Double) ID of the liquid\par
name(Name) the property of the specified liquid\par
\par
The 'name' can be:\par
X(Double) stands for the x-position of the liquid\par
Y(Double) stands for the y-position of the liquid\par
Xsp(Double) stands for the x-axis speed of the liquid\par
Ysp(Double) stands for the y-axis speed of the liquid\par
Fdir(Double) stands for the direction of the force field\par
Fval(Double) stands for the acceleration of the force field\par
Fmax(Double) stands for the max speed of the force field\par
\f2\par
\f1 [Warp]\par
Warp(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 ).\cf4\i name\par
\cf0\i0 id(Double) ID of the warp\par
name(Name) the property of the specified warp\par
\f2\par
\f0 The 'name' can be:\par
X(Double) stands for the x-position of the warp entrance\par
Y(Double) stands for the y-position of the warp entrance\par
Ex(Double) stands for the x-position of the warp exit\par
Ey(Double) stands for the y-position of the warp exit\par
Xsp(Double) stands for the x-axis speed of the warp\par
Ysp(Double) stands for the y-axis speed of the warp\par
Cannon(Double) stands for the flight duration of the pipe type warp\par
Starcnt(Double) stands for the number of stars needed to enter the warp\par
Starmsg(String) stands for the message displayed when the player does not have enough stars to enter the warp\par
Locked(Double) stands for whether a key is needed to enter the warp\par
Bomb(Double) stands for whether a bomb is needed to enter the warp\par
Noyoshi(Double) stands for whether mounts are allowed to enter the warp\par
Canpick(Double) stands for whether items can be carried when entering the warp\par
Mini(Double) stande for whether this warp is only available for mini players\f2\par
\par
\f1 [Bgp]\par
\f0 Bgp(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 ).\cf4\i name\cf7\i0\par
\cf0 id(Double) ID of the background picture\par
name(Name) the property of the specified background picture\par
\par
The 'name' can be:\par
Splitcount(Double) stands for how many times the picture is splitted. Different parts have different configurations.\par
Splitter(String) the y-positions of the splitting points, consists of a series of integers separated by commas.\par
Zsp(String) the offset constants of the picture parts, consists of a series of floating point values separated by commas.\par
Movesp(String) the moving speed of the picture parts, consists of a series of floating point values separated by commas.\par
Offset(String) the current offset value of the picture parts, consists of a series of floating point values separated by commas.\par
\par
[Text]\par
Text(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 ).\cf4\i name\par
\cf0\i0 ID (Double) the exclusice ID of the text object\par
name (Name) the property of the specified bitmap\par
\par
The 'name' can be:\par
x (Double) stands for the x-position of the text\par
y (Double) stands for the y-position of the text\par
text (String) stands for the content of the text\par
hide (Double/Bool) stands for whether the text is not visible\par
\par
[Bitmap]\par
Bitmap(\cf4\i id\cf0\i0 ).\cf4\i name\par
\cf0\i0 Id (Double) the exclusive ID of the bitmap object\par
name (Name) the property of the specified bitmap\par
\par
The 'name' can be:\par
destx (Double) stands for the x-position of the bitmap\par
desty (Double) stands for the y-position of the bitmap\par
scalex (Double) stands for the x-axis scale ratio of the bitmap\par
scaley (Double) stands for the y-axis scale ratio of the bitmap\par
rotatang (Double) stands for the the rotation angle of the bitmap\par
hide (Double/Bool) stands for whether the bitmap is not visible\par
